        "narrative_summary": "The TP53 c.666G>A variant, also reported as NM_000546.6:c.666G>A and resulting in a synonymous p.Pro222= change, has been identified in tumor sequencing studies. It appears in the coding region of TP53 and has been observed in two distinct cancer types.\n\nIn a 2017 study of sporadic chordoma, the variant was listed among coding mutations detected in tumor samples, but the authors did not provide an interpretation of its clinical significance [PMC5638846]. A separate 2017 osteosarcoma sequencing effort also reported TP53 c.666G>A as one of the coding substitutions present in the cohort, again without any claim regarding pathogenicity or clinical relevance [PMC5490007].\n\nNo functional assays, population frequency data, or computational predictions were presented in the extracted evidence, and the available reports do not assign a pathogenic or benign classification. Consequently, there is no direct conflict between studies, but the lack of interpretive data creates uncertainty about the variant’s impact.\n\nGiven the current evidence, TP53 c.666G>A remains a variant of uncertain significance, as it has been observed in cancer genomes without supporting functional or epidemiological data to clarify its role in disease.",
